      {
        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "Why: below pH 3.8, most oxalate is still protonated as hydrogen oxalate, so free \\( \\mathrm{C_2O_4^{2-}} \\) is limited. Around **pH = pKa2 = 3.8**, the fully deprotonated oxalate form starts becoming substantial, which is the form that both **binds Ca²⁺ strongly** and **enters the low-solubility solid**. Because Ca–oxalate complexation is fairly favorable \\( \\log K \\approx 3.2 \\), oxalate is effectively “captured” by calcium once enough \\( \\mathrm{C_2O_4^{2-}} \\) appears, so precipitation tends to turn on near this region.",
